# Dispatch for Telex — Core Standards

## Guiding Principle

This plugin will be scrutinized by people who are skeptical of AI-assisted development and actively looking for any excuse to dismiss it as "vibe-coded garbage." Every single line of code must be production-quality, rigorously defensible, and beyond reproach. There is no such thing as "good enough for now." If it wouldn't survive a WordPress core team code review, rewrite it.

## Architecture

The plugin follows a strict 5-layer architecture. Never skip or bypass layers:

```
React UI (src/)  →  REST API (Telex_REST)  →  Service Layer (includes/)  →  SDK (lib/telex-sdk/)  →  WP HTTP Client (Telex_WP_Http_Client)
```

- The React UI only talks to the REST layer — never calls PHP service classes directly
- Service classes never make HTTP requests directly — always through the SDK and `Telex_WP_Http_Client`
- DTOs (`Telex_Project`, `Telex_Build_File`, `Telex_Api_Credentials`) cross layer boundaries as immutable value objects

## Universal Non-Negotiables

- No `var_dump`, `error_log`, `print_r`, `console.log`, or `debugger` in committed code
- No commented-out code blocks
- No TODOs or FIXMEs left in committed code
- No dead code — if it isn't used, remove it
- PHPDoc on every public method: `@param`, `@return`, `@throws`
- Imperative commit messages: "Add circuit breaker reset command", not "fixed stuff"

## Before Every Commit

```bash
make lint    # ESLint + Stylelint + PHP_CodeSniffer — must pass with zero errors
make test    # PHPUnit — must pass clean
make build   # Webpack — must produce a clean output
```
